            <fr:title text="A characterisation of compact topological spaces">A characterisation of compact topological spaces</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For a topological space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> the following are equivalent: 
  <html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is compact; </html:li>
    <html:li> For all topological spaces <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, the projection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _Y : X \times  Y \to  Y]]></fr:tex> is <html:em>closed</html:em>. </html:li>
    <html:li> For all <html:em><fr:link href="/topl-VV9N/" title="Spectral spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-VV9N/" display-uri="topl-VV9N" type="local">spectral spaces</fr:link></html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, the projection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _Y : X \times  Y \to  Y]]></fr:tex> is <html:em>closed</html:em>. </html:li></html:ol></html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    (1) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Rightarrow ]]></fr:tex> (2): Suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is compact. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C \subseteq  X \times  Y]]></fr:tex> be a closed set. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  Y]]></fr:tex> be an element outside <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _Y[C]]]></fr:tex>. This way, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \times  \{y\}]]></fr:tex> is disjoint from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex>, which implies we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \times  \{y\} \subseteq  \overline {C}]]></fr:tex> for the open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {C}]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is quasi-compact, we can indeed find an open neighbourhood <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \times  U \subseteq  \overline {C}]]></fr:tex>. This implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> has an open neighbourhood <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> disjiont from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _Y[C]]]></fr:tex>, hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _Y[C]]]></fr:tex> is closed, and this implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _Y]]></fr:tex> is closed.
  </html:p>
  <html:p>
    (2) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Rightarrow ]]></fr:tex> (3) is trivial. For (3) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Rightarrow ]]></fr:tex> (1): Suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is not quasi-compact. Then we can find an infinite cover <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X = \bigcup _{i\in  I}U_i]]></fr:tex> where any proper subcover will not be the total space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Consider the power set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\wp (I)]]></fr:tex> as a spectral space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2^I]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> the Sierpinski space. In particular, for any finite subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> there is an open subset
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ V_K := \{J\in \wp (I)\mid K \subseteq  J\}. ]]></fr:tex>
    Consider the following subspace <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\wp (I) \times  X]]></fr:tex>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ M := \{(J,x)\mid x \in  \bigcap _{j\in  J}\overline {U_j}\} ]]></fr:tex>
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(J,x)\not \in  M]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  U_j]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j\in  J]]></fr:tex>. This way, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(J,x) \in  V_{\{j\}} \times  U_j \subseteq  \overline {M}]]></fr:tex>, which implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> is closed. Now by assumption, the image <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi [M]]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\wp (I)]]></fr:tex> is the subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\wp (I)-\{I\}]]></fr:tex>, which is <html:em>not</html:em> closed, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{I\}]]></fr:tex> is not open in the product topology.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
