            <fr:display-uri>topl-GIFJ</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/topl-GIFJ/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Image finite posets are locally spectral">Image finite posets are locally spectral</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> an <fr:link href="/topl-Q322/" title="Image finite posets" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-Q322/" display-uri="topl-Q322" type="local">image finite poset</fr:link> with Alexandroff topology, it is a <fr:link href="/topl-VV9N/" title="Spectral spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-VV9N/" display-uri="topl-VV9N" type="local">locally spectral</fr:link> space.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>13</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    In the Alexandroff topology, opens are exactly upward closed sets. Hence, compact opens are exactly finitely generated, hence finite by being image finite, upsets. They evidently form a basis, and are closed under intersections. 
  </html:p>
  <html:p>
    Hence, it suffices to show it is sober. Suppose now we have an irreducible closed set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex>. Consider the following procedure:
    <html:ol><html:li>Pick some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_0\in  C]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
      <html:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\downarrow  x_i \subsetneq  C]]></fr:tex>, then pick <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{i+1}\in  C - \downarrow  x_i]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ol>
    If this process never terminate, then we have an infinite strictly increasing chain of elements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_0 < x_1 < \cdots ]]></fr:tex>, contradictory to image finiteness of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Hence, we must have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C = \downarrow  x_i]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>, which implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> has the generic point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_i]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>6</fr:month>
              <fr:day>13</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/schm-BP3S/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>schm-BP3S</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/schm-BP3S/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Schemes from image finite posets">Schemes from image finite posets</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:link href="/topl-Q322/" title="Image finite posets" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-Q322/" display-uri="topl-Q322" type="local">image finite poset</fr:link>. Recall from <fr:link href="/topl-GIFJ/" title="Image finite posets are locally spectral" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-GIFJ/" display-uri="topl-GIFJ" type="local">Lemma <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-GIFJ/" display-uri="topl-GIFJ" /></fr:link> that as a topological space it is <fr:link href="/topl-VV9N/" title="Spectral spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-VV9N/" display-uri="topl-VV9N" type="local">locally spectral</fr:link>. It is a <fr:link href="/schm-86OJ/" title="Scheme" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-86OJ/" display-uri="schm-86OJ" type="local">scheme</fr:link>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>13</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  We need to define a structural sheaf on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. For any upward closed susbet <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, we define 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \mathcal {O}_{X}(U) := \mathcal {U}(U), ]]></fr:tex>
  the distributive lattice of upward closed subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>. This is a sheaf, because if we have a union <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = \bigcup _{i\in  I}U_i]]></fr:tex> with an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V_i \in  \mathcal {O}_{X}(U_i)]]></fr:tex>, which is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V_i \subseteq  U_i]]></fr:tex> upward closed, which agrees on intersections,
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ V_i \cap  U_j = V_j \cap  U_i, ]]></fr:tex>
  then there is a unique <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V \subseteq  U]]></fr:tex> given by 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ V = \bigcup _{i\in  I}V_i, ]]></fr:tex>
  such that 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ V \cap  U_j = \bigcup _{i\in  I}V_i \cap  U_j = \bigcup _{i\in  I}V_j \cap  U_i = V_j \cap  \bigcup _{i\in  I}U_i = V_j \cap  U = V_j. ]]></fr:tex>
  This is in fact a <fr:link href="/schm-V16H/" title="Locally distributed space" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-V16H/" display-uri="schm-V16H" type="local">locally distributed space</fr:link>, because for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex>,
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \mathcal {O}_{X,x} \cong  \mathcal {O}_{X}(\uparrow  x) \cong  \mathcal {U}(\uparrow  x), ]]></fr:tex>
  which is <fr:link href="/idem-comm-75C1/" title="Local distributive lattice" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-75C1/" display-uri="idem-comm-75C1" type="local">local</fr:link> because <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\uparrow  x]]></fr:tex> has a root (cf. <fr:link href="/idem-comm-E2I8/" title="Equivalent formulation of locality" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-E2I8/" display-uri="idem-comm-E2I8" type="local">Remark <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-E2I8/" display-uri="idem-comm-E2I8" /></fr:link>). Finally, this is a scheme, because by construction for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex>, the open neighbourhood <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\uparrow  x]]></fr:tex> is affine <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\uparrow  x,\mathcal {O}_{\uparrow  x}) \cong  \operatorname {Spec}\mathcal {U}(\uparrow  x)]]></fr:tex>.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>6</fr:month>
              <fr:day>11</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/topl-9BKS/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>topl-9BKS</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/topl-9BKS/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Quasi-compact continuous maps">Quasi-compact continuous maps</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  We say a continuous map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : Y \to  X]]></fr:tex> between topological spaces is <html:em>quasi-compact</html:em> if the inverse image of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> preserves compact opens. This is mainly useful when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X,Y]]></fr:tex> are both <fr:link href="/topl-VV9N/" title="Spectral spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-VV9N/" display-uri="topl-VV9N" type="local">spectral</fr:link>.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>6</fr:month>
              <fr:day>8</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/schm-80MC/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>schm-80MC</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/schm-80MC/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="A scheme is affine iff it is spectral">A scheme is affine iff it is spectral</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  A scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is affine iff its underlying topological space is <fr:link href="/topl-VV9N/" title="Spectral spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-VV9N/" display-uri="topl-VV9N" type="local">spectral</fr:link>, i.e. iff it is <html:em>compact</html:em> and <fr:link href="/topl-GW93/" title="Quasi-separated spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-GW93/" display-uri="topl-GW93" type="local">quasi-separated</fr:link>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>8</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a scheme whose underlying topological space is spectral. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> be the distributive lattice of compact open subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{U_i\}_{i\in  I}]]></fr:tex> be a finite family of affine open covers of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_i]]></fr:tex>, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_i]]></fr:tex> is affine, and affine schemes are determined by their underlying topological space (see <fr:link href="/schm-1I73/" title="Affine schemes are determined by topology" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-1I73/" display-uri="schm-1I73" type="local">Remark <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-1I73/" display-uri="schm-1I73" /></fr:link>), we must have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{U_i} \cong  D_i]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_i]]></fr:tex> is the principle quotient of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> corresponding to the compact open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_i]]></fr:tex>. This way, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{X}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{D}]]></fr:tex> agree on this open cover, which implies that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{X} \cong  \mathcal {O}_{D}]]></fr:tex>.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>6</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-EA6S/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-EA6S</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/idem-comm-EA6S/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Spectra are spectral spaces">Spectra are spectral spaces</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For any distributive lattice <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/topl-VV9N/" title="Spectral spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-VV9N/" display-uri="topl-VV9N" type="local">spectral</fr:link>. This gives us a functor
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} : \mathbf {DL}^{\mathrm {op}} \to  \mathbf {Spec} ]]></fr:tex>
  from distributive lattices to spectral spaces.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    Notice that we have a homeomorphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ O_p \cong  \operatorname {Spec} D/p, ]]></fr:tex>
    where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_p]]></fr:tex> is viewed as an open subspace of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>. Hence, we only need to show <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is compact and sober for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_p]]></fr:tex> be the complement of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_p]]></fr:tex> for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  D]]></fr:tex>, and suppose we have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \bigcap _{i\in  I}C_{p_i} = \emptyset . ]]></fr:tex>
    This means that the family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p_i\}_{i\in  I}]]></fr:tex> is inconsistent, thus by compactness, finitely many of them is already inconsistent. Thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is compact, and compact opens in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> are all of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_p]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  D]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>
  <html:p>
    To show <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/topl-FII1/" title="Sober spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-FII1/" display-uri="topl-FII1" type="local">sober</fr:link>, by <fr:link href="/idem-comm-W1VU/" title="Irreducible closed subsets of spectra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W1VU/" display-uri="idem-comm-W1VU" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W1VU/" display-uri="idem-comm-W1VU" /></fr:link> any irreducible closed set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I]]></fr:tex> corresponds to some prime ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>. This way, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> be the complement of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>. We now have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I = \overline {\{x\}}]]></fr:tex>, because
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ x \not \in  O_p \Leftrightarrow  x \in  C_p \Leftrightarrow  x \not \models  p \Leftrightarrow  p \in  I. ]]></fr:tex>
    Thus we indeed have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I = \bigcap _{p\in  I}C_p = \bigcap _{x\not \in  O_p}C_p = \overline {\{x\}}]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>
  <html:p>
    Finally to show a map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : D \to  E]]></fr:tex> induces a continuous map
